1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,580
Okay, so today we will finish the
Greeks by discussing Aristotle.

2
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:11,920
And a lot of what I will say
today will be controversial.

3
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:17,000
So feel free to challenge me.

4
00:00:17,060 --> 00:00:19,180
Feel free to ask for clarification.

5
00:00:19,980 --> 00:00:23,760
Feel free to ask any questions.

6
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:26,520
So here's my argument.

7
00:00:27,240 --> 00:00:29,240
Aristotle is a paradox.

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,400
He is one of the mysterious
figures in world history.

9
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:35,960
He's one of the most famous, but
he's one of the most mysterious.

10
00:00:36,480 --> 00:00:38,420
He's a paradox for three reasons, okay?

11
00:00:39,560 --> 00:00:42,940
The first reason is he is considered

12
00:00:42,940 --> 00:00:47,960
to be one of the greatest
philosophers in human history.

13
00:00:48,140 --> 00:00:53,440
He's next to Plato. He's
certainly as influential as Plato.

14
00:00:54,940 --> 00:00:58,880
But what is unique about him
is we do not have anything,

15
00:01:00,180 --> 00:01:02,300
originally written by him, okay?

16
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:04,440
We have no text that

17
00:01:04,440 --> 00:01:08,240
we believe was personally written by him.

18
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:10,680
And that's unique in human history, okay?

19
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:13,080
We say Shakespeare was a great writer and

20
00:01:13,080 --> 00:01:16,000
we can prove it or show
it by reading his text.

21
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,920
We believe Aristotle is a great thinker,

22
00:01:20,020 --> 00:01:22,760
a great writer, but we have no evidence,

23
00:01:22,900 --> 00:01:26,300
no text, to show us this is the case.

24
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:27,960
We believe so, okay?

25
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:29,740
So this is the first paradox.

26
00:01:29,740 --> 00:01:30,660
The second paradox of Aristotle.

27
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:37,640
Second paradox of Aristotle is
he was a very prolific writer

28
00:01:37,640 --> 00:01:41,200
and thinker. In fact, we believe he,

29
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:44,380
there's about 200 works
attributed to Aristotle.

30
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:47,960
What is unique about his work

31
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:52,660
is the range of his
thinking and his research.

32
00:01:52,940 --> 00:01:57,420
So he's written a book on politics,

33
00:01:57,700 --> 00:01:59,640
right? What is the best political system?

34
00:01:59,740 --> 00:02:03,560
He's written a book on poetics,

35
00:02:03,660 --> 00:02:06,800
theater, basically. What
makes for a good tragedy?

36
00:02:07,260 --> 00:02:10,040
He's written a book on ethics.

37
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:12,820
What is a good life?
What makes a good person?

38
00:02:13,220 --> 00:02:15,060
He's written a book on rhetoric.

39
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:19,280
How do you convince the
audience that you are correct?

40
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:24,640
He's also written books on physics.

41
00:02:25,340 --> 00:02:28,280
He's written books on metaphysics.

42
00:02:28,460 --> 00:02:29,720
He's written books on physics.

43
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:31,100
He's written books on biology.

44
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:33,160
Okay? The range is just incredible.

45
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:38,900
We have no analog in
human history like him.

46
00:02:39,500 --> 00:02:45,020
He's simply unique in the
range of his curiosity.

47
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:50,020
Second paradox. The third
paradox is most problematic.

48
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:56,180
We know that Aristotle studied
under Plato for 20 years.

49
00:02:57,020 --> 00:02:59,700
And so we also believe that Aristotle
studied under Plato for 20 years.

50
00:02:59,700 --> 00:03:05,260
Aristotle was Plato's most famous student.

51
00:03:06,820 --> 00:03:11,240
The paradox is Aristotle's understanding

52
00:03:11,240 --> 00:03:14,360
of the universe is radically

53
00:03:14,360 --> 00:03:19,020
opposed to Plato's
understanding of the universe.

54
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:22,880
Okay? And that's, again,
is unique in human history.

55
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:28,820
You would think the best student would carry
on the master's work or at least build on it,

56
00:03:28,860 --> 00:03:30,320
right? But Aristotle,

57
00:03:30,860 --> 00:03:31,920
his understanding of the universe,

58
00:03:32,280 --> 00:03:37,220
is in conflict with Plato's work.

59
00:03:37,440 --> 00:03:40,020
In fact, you could also argue that

60
00:03:40,020 --> 00:03:44,320
Aristotle is negating Plato's worldview.

61
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:47,040
Okay? So let me explain how.

62
00:03:47,380 --> 00:03:50,160
So we know Plato. We know that for Plato,

63
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:53,580
there is a god, and it's
called the form of the good.

64
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:59,680
And the form of the good
is what is the best.

65
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,420
It's eternal, perfect,

66
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:04,640
and immutable.

67
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:06,620
Okay? Now,

68
00:04:06,720 --> 00:04:11,520
the form of the good
emanates other perfections.

69
00:04:11,560 --> 00:04:14,960
What he calls the form of the ideal.

70
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:19,460
Okay? So these are concepts like
justice and beauty and reason.

71
00:04:20,040 --> 00:04:23,020
And then these concepts
manifest themselves

72
00:04:23,020 --> 00:04:28,160
in forms like horse,

73
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:29,500
right? Or a woman.

74
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:32,400
Okay? And these are
like the ideal, perfect,

75
00:04:32,660 --> 00:04:36,420
immutable, eternal manifestations.

76
00:04:37,940 --> 00:04:40,420
Okay? So there's only one
horse. It's up in heaven.

77
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:45,600
Everything else is a copy of this
horse or imitation of this horse.

78
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:47,780
Okay? So we live in a shadow realm.

79
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:51,080
Okay? A shadow realm where
everything is imitation.

80
00:04:51,380 --> 00:04:53,140
Okay? This is our reality.
It's a shadow reality.

81
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:59,660
And that's why art and poetry
and theater are so important.

82
00:04:59,660 --> 00:05:01,040
And that's why music and
theater are so bad. Because

83
00:05:01,040 --> 00:05:05,820
they are really an
imitation of an imitation.

84
00:05:06,280 --> 00:05:10,740
Okay? So this is Plato's hierarchy.

85
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:14,140
So from this hierarchy and

86
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:17,360
this world view, we can
make certain extrapolations.

87
00:05:17,580 --> 00:05:20,600
Okay? The first
extrapolation is for Plato,

88
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:25,200
what is good is if you approach or

89
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:26,840
return to the form of the good.

90
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:28,240
What is evil?

91
00:05:28,240 --> 00:05:33,220
What is bad is if you move
away from the form of the good.

92
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:35,260
Okay? Right?

93
00:05:35,340 --> 00:05:39,900
So poetry is evil. Mathematics is good.

94
00:05:40,080 --> 00:05:42,620
Okay? Now, why is mathematics good?

95
00:05:42,820 --> 00:05:44,520
Because mathematics is what allows

96
00:05:44,520 --> 00:05:49,180
you to approach the

97
00:05:49,180 --> 00:05:50,520
form of the good.

98
00:05:50,900 --> 00:05:53,680
All right? So let me give
you an example of this.

99
00:05:53,860 --> 00:05:56,500
Okay? Let's say there's a circle.

100
00:05:56,620 --> 00:06:01,480
Right? What Plato argues is
no matter how hard you try,

101
00:06:01,780 --> 00:06:03,240
you could never,

102
00:06:03,300 --> 00:06:08,080
ever draw a circle in this world.

103
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:11,120
Okay? Because a circle has an edge.

104
00:06:11,480 --> 00:06:15,180
So it's like literally impossible for
you to create something without an edge.

105
00:06:15,320 --> 00:06:17,060
Right? You're like, well,
I can draw on the computer.

106
00:06:17,540 --> 00:06:20,480
But if you go at a microscopic
level, you will always find an edge.

107
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:22,800
Okay? So how do you create a circle?

108
00:06:23,120 --> 00:06:26,080
Well, you create a circle by
imagining it in your head.

109
00:06:26,940 --> 00:06:28,220
Okay? So you draw a circle.

110
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:32,760
So what you're really doing
is you're imagining the circle

111
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:36,700
because you're accessing
the realm of the forms.

112
00:06:36,740 --> 00:06:38,160
You're approaching from the good.

113
00:06:38,740 --> 00:06:40,900
Okay? So it's only pure,

114
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:43,540
it is only through a
process of pure thought,

115
00:06:43,720 --> 00:06:46,500
pure philosophy, pure mathematics that

116
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:50,960
you can actually start
to understand this world.

117
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:58,300
All right? That's Plato's
understanding of the world.

118
00:06:59,460 --> 00:07:02,340
Aristotle has a completely
different understanding.

119
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:04,820
Okay? So Aristotle starts with this.

120
00:07:05,040 --> 00:07:06,580
That God's a prime mover.

121
00:07:06,740 --> 00:07:10,360
Okay? So the prime mover,
just imagine a big bag.

122
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:12,700
Right? Something explodes.

123
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:14,380
Boom. It moves.

124
00:07:14,580 --> 00:07:17,720
And it forces other
things to move as well.

125
00:07:18,220 --> 00:07:22,360
So what Aristotle is saying is
everything is really in motion.

126
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:23,820
Okay? Everything is change.

127
00:07:25,700 --> 00:07:29,040
Because it was all caused
by the prime mover.

128
00:07:31,760 --> 00:07:34,600
And in Plato's, sorry,
in Aristotle's world,

129
00:07:34,760 --> 00:07:36,920
what is good is the good.

130
00:07:36,940 --> 00:07:41,720
But what he's saying is if the thing
that changes moves towards its purpose.

131
00:07:41,940 --> 00:07:44,560
Okay? Or the word he uses is called telos.

132
00:07:45,240 --> 00:07:47,480
Telos. Okay?

133
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:51,300
If you're moving towards your purpose,
you are doing good in this world.

134
00:07:51,460 --> 00:07:56,080
If you're moving away from your purpose,
you're doing bad in this world.

135
00:07:56,140 --> 00:08:00,520
Okay? So the example is a soldier. The purpose
of a soldier is to fight and win wars.

136
00:08:00,920 --> 00:08:04,140
So if you go fight and you do
your best, you're doing good.

137
00:08:04,940 --> 00:08:06,920
But if you run away from
a war, you're doing bad.

138
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:08,500
you're doing bad, okay?

139
00:08:09,700 --> 00:08:14,480
So this is Aristotle's worldview

140
00:08:14,480 --> 00:08:15,940
and as you can understand,

141
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:17,800
as you can see,

142
00:08:17,940 --> 00:08:22,860
these two worldviews cannot harmonize.

143
00:08:22,940 --> 00:08:24,940
They are in conflict with each other.

144
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:27,560
You have either one or the other, okay?

145
00:08:27,980 --> 00:08:33,760
So let me highlight the three major
differences between these two worldviews,

146
00:08:33,760 --> 00:08:34,980
okay?

147
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:37,840
And again, I need to emphasize this.

148
00:08:38,040 --> 00:08:40,360
I am not an expert on Aristotle.

149
00:08:40,480 --> 00:08:42,000
I'm not an expert on Plato, okay?

150
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:45,200
So I am committing oversimplifications.

151
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:51,240
Scholars who are experts will
hear this and be outraged, okay?

152
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:52,860
But for the purpose of this class,

153
00:08:53,140 --> 00:08:57,120
I feel these oversimplifications
provide clarity, okay?

154
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:02,840
Alright, so the first oversimplification
is Plato is what we call a rationalist.

155
00:09:06,660 --> 00:09:09,100
Aristotle is what we call
an empiricist, alright?

156
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:12,240
So these are two big words, but

157
00:09:12,240 --> 00:09:14,280
the rationalist is just
someone who believes that

158
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:18,040
you can access the truth
through pure thought, okay?

159
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:21,100
Mathematics. An empiricist is someone who

160
00:09:21,100 --> 00:09:24,120
believes you can only access
the truth through observation

161
00:09:24,120 --> 00:09:26,480
and what we call induction,

162
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:31,280
okay? Inductive logic, alright?

163
00:09:32,100 --> 00:09:34,820
So if I see a woman wearing a dress

164
00:09:34,820 --> 00:09:37,780
and I see a woman wearing
a dress, and a third,

165
00:09:37,880 --> 00:09:38,840
I'm like, okay,

166
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:44,480
well from this I can
logically deduce or induce

167
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:49,160
that all women wear dresses and that's
what separates women from men, okay?

168
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:52,960
So for Aristotle to seek the truth,

169
00:09:53,060 --> 00:09:57,280
you have to observe and
you have to induce, okay?

170
00:09:57,420 --> 00:09:58,820
So that's the first major difference.

171
00:09:59,060 --> 00:10:03,000
Second major difference is Plato
is what we call a dualist.

172
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:06,200
And I'm going to give you a little
bit of a background on that.

173
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:07,440
Aristotle is what we call a materialist.

174
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:13,320
A dualist is someone who believes
that there's a body and a soul, okay?

175
00:10:13,540 --> 00:10:15,540
And if you believe
there's a body and a soul,

176
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:18,720
you also believe the soul
is more important because

177
00:10:18,720 --> 00:10:23,080
the soul is eternal, whereas
the body will decay and die.

178
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:28,820
Aristotle, he's a materialist, so

179
00:10:28,820 --> 00:10:32,900
for him the focus is on the body
and what happens to the body, okay?

180
00:10:32,960 --> 00:10:36,320
There may be a soul, there may not
be a soul, he doesn't really care.

181
00:10:36,460 --> 00:10:40,020
For him it doesn't really matter. What
matters is what happens to the body, okay?

182
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:45,320
The third major difference is Plato
believes in the idea of a mutability,

183
00:10:45,620 --> 00:10:47,540
okay, or a call eternity.

184
00:10:51,240 --> 00:10:56,800
For Aristotle, almost
nothing is a mutable.

185
00:10:56,900 --> 00:10:58,260
Most things are a mutable, okay?

186
00:10:58,440 --> 00:11:02,280
The only thing that's a really a mutable is
really God, but everything else is mutable.

187
00:11:02,380 --> 00:11:05,820
It will change over time.
And so, for Aristotle,

188
00:11:06,340 --> 00:11:07,580
the concept is infinity.

189
00:11:08,460 --> 00:11:13,020
Things will always change, things will
always move, there's no stopping movement.

190
00:11:14,860 --> 00:11:18,620
But for Plato, things are eternal,

191
00:11:18,760 --> 00:11:19,960
there's a grand design,

192
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:23,400
and nothing that changes really matters.

193
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:25,380
It doesn't really affect the grand design.

194
00:11:26,040 --> 00:11:27,320
So for him, it's eternity.

195
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:32,220
So these are the three major
differences between Plato and Aristotle.

196
00:11:32,600 --> 00:11:37,440
Now what's really interesting for
us is this conflict between Plato

197
00:11:37,440 --> 00:11:42,540
and Aristotle is what will inform the philosophical
debate for all of Western civilization.

198
00:11:43,700 --> 00:11:46,820
So there are two major
camps in Western philosophy.

199
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,480
There is the rationalist camp,

200
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:54,020
so people like Descartes, and then there are
the empiricists, so people like David Hume.

201
00:11:54,580 --> 00:11:56,340
And for most of Western history,

202
00:11:57,880 --> 00:12:02,600
philosophers like Descartes will go back and
forth between these two extremes, either the

203
00:12:03,140 --> 00:12:06,060
Platonic ideal or the Aristotle reality.

204
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:10,820
Does that make sense? Is this clear?

205
00:12:11,240 --> 00:12:15,700
Any questions? Sure,

206
00:12:15,840 --> 00:12:36,840
go ahead. Yeah, so
that's a great question.

207
00:12:36,980 --> 00:12:39,460
And for Plato, okay, what we,

208
00:12:39,580 --> 00:12:42,440
like our lives, the reality
we live in is not real.

209
00:12:43,380 --> 00:12:47,120
It's ephemeral. Whereas the form of
the good, that's what's concrete.

210
00:12:47,620 --> 00:12:50,040
That's what's eternal, okay?

211
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:54,000
So I mean, like, I understand
that's counterintuitive to us,

212
00:12:54,140 --> 00:12:58,300
but the reason why it's kind of
counterintuitive to us is because we're mainly influenced by Aristotle, right?

213
00:12:58,660 --> 00:13:01,260
We live, we are materialist, right?

214
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:02,680
Science is materialistic.

215
00:13:03,880 --> 00:13:07,540
But back then, and I would say back

216
00:13:07,540 --> 00:13:10,320
then in Plato's time, and
for most of human history,

217
00:13:10,740 --> 00:13:13,340
it was assumed that

218
00:13:13,340 --> 00:13:16,280
our world was transitory,

219
00:13:16,280 --> 00:13:18,440
or transient, or ephemeral, okay?

220
00:13:18,680 --> 00:13:20,340
And it was a spirit world, okay?

221
00:13:20,460 --> 00:13:23,640
That was real. And that was eternal.

222
00:13:25,120 --> 00:13:26,520
Does that make sense?

223
00:13:27,100 --> 00:13:29,320
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Yeah, I think so.

224
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:33,940
Okay. Okay. Again, this is
oversimplification, okay?

225
00:13:34,520 --> 00:13:37,580
Like, if you go to a scholar
who understands itself,

226
00:13:37,840 --> 00:13:40,120
I will probably, he'll
probably criticize me, okay?

227
00:13:40,180 --> 00:13:44,740
But I'm saying that for the purpose of this class,
and for our understanding of Western civilization,

228
00:13:45,220 --> 00:13:49,060
this will do, okay? Just understand there's
a major conflict between Plato and Aristotle.

229
00:13:49,340 --> 00:13:50,720
This will go on for thousands of years.

230
00:13:50,960 --> 00:13:55,400
This will inform the debate
in Western civilization, okay?

231
00:13:55,440 --> 00:13:57,400
This is the fundamental
debate in Western philosophy.

232
00:13:58,660 --> 00:14:03,420
All right? So let's go back to,
let's summarize where we are.

233
00:14:04,880 --> 00:14:06,400
Aristotle is a paradox, right?

234
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:09,100
We have nothing that he wrote originally.

235
00:14:10,180 --> 00:14:12,760
The range of his work is just incredible.

236
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:15,080
It's unique in human history.

237
00:14:15,940 --> 00:14:18,060
And then lastly, even though

238
00:14:18,060 --> 00:14:21,460
we know Aristotle sat under Plato
for like 20 years, at least,

239
00:14:22,660 --> 00:14:24,840
Aristotle came up with a very different

240
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:28,440
conceptualization of the universe.
In fact, it is indirect.

241
00:14:28,440 --> 00:14:32,520
It's an indirect conflict with
Plato's understanding, okay?

242
00:14:33,540 --> 00:14:36,620
So how is this possible?
How are these paradox,

243
00:14:36,800 --> 00:14:38,420
how can we resolve these paradoxes?

244
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:42,000
Okay, so I'm gonna make an argument.

245
00:14:43,240 --> 00:14:47,320
And I will slowly make this argument,
but it is a controversial argument, okay?

246
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:52,260
